{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477858","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477858"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:06:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:06:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14881"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14881","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14881"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.78,0.1,0.02,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7572"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59155"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7572","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7572"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14881"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44566"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"303"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1142"},{"type":"tags","id":"2479"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18513"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43565"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44224"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59155","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59155"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA four-month-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of worsening respiratory symptoms. He initially developed a runny nose and mild cough which has progressed to noisy breathing and increased work of breathing. He was born at 34 weeks gestation and spent two weeks in the special care nursery. He has no other medical conditions and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed with subcostal and intercostal recession. His pulse rate is 160/min, respiratory rate 60/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. There is nasal congestion with clear rhinorrhoea. Chest auscultation reveals bilateral wheeze and fine crackles. His capillary refill time is two seconds. A chest X-ray shows right upper lobe collapse.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Viral croup","Respiratory syncytial virus infection","Bacterial pneumonia","Acute asthma","Pertussis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis infant presents with a typical course of bronchiolitis, which is most commonly caused by respiratory syncytial virus (RSV) in this age group. The progression from upper respiratory symptoms to lower respiratory involvement over several days is characteristic. His history of prematurity puts him at higher risk for severe disease. The finding of right upper lobe collapse on chest X-ray is a classic radiological feature of RSV bronchiolitis, thought to be due to mucus plugging of the bronchioles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERespiratory syncytial virus infection\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with rhinorrhoea and cough that progresses to increased work of breathing, wheeze, and crackles. The presence of these signs, along with the typical age group, seasonal timing, and characteristic right upper lobe collapse makes this the most likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBacterial pneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with more acute onset, higher fever, and focal chest signs rather than the diffuse wheeze and crackles seen here. The progression from upper respiratory symptoms would be unusual, and the pattern of right upper lobe collapse would be less typical.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPertussis\u003C/strong\u003E characteristically presents with paroxysmal coughing spells followed by an inspiratory \u0027whoop\u0027, which is not described here. The progression and examination findings are not consistent with pertussis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EViral croup\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with a barking cough and stridor due to subglottic inflammation. The presence of wheeze and crackles throughout the chest would be unusual, and upper lobe collapse would not be expected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute asthma\u003C/strong\u003E would be unusual at this age, as the first presentation of asthma rarely occurs before 12 months of age. Additionally, the progression from upper respiratory symptoms and the radiological findings are more consistent with viral bronchiolitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of RSV bronchiolitis is primarily supportive, including oxygen therapy if required, maintaining hydration, and careful monitoring. Most cases can be managed at home, but hospital admission may be needed for oxygen therapy or feeding support, particularly in infants with risk factors such as prematurity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Respiratory syncytial virus (RSV) typically presents with rhinorrhoea progressing to lower respiratory tract symptoms over several days.","Risk factors for severe RSV infection include age under 6 months, prematurity, and underlying cardiorespiratory conditions.","The diagnosis of RSV is primarily clinical, with rapid antigen testing available but not routinely required.","Right upper lobe collapse is a classic radiological finding in RSV bronchiolitis."],"references":["Kaler J, Hussain A, Patel K, Hernandez T, Ray S. Respiratory Syncytial Virus: A Comprehensive Review of Transmission, Pathophysiology, and Manifestation. Cureus. 2023 Mar 18;15(3):e36342. doi: 10.7759/cureus.36342. PMID: 37082497; PMCID: PMC10111061."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44566"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14881"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44566","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44566"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-05T12:32:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-05T12:33:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7572"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59155"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Di